Create a hyper-realistic editorial film portrait, single subject, single frame, like a real photograph pulled out of a magazine — not concept art, not 3D render, not AI-glossy.

Subject
{{subject}}

Scene & atmosphere
- Setting: {{scene}}
- Mood: {{mood}}
- Pose & gaze: {{pose_and_gaze}}
- The image must feel observed, not directed. Imperfect composition, real body weight, real fabric drape.

Camera & film
- Film / camera signature: {{film_stock}}
- Lens & aperture: {{lens_and_aperture}}
- Lighting: {{lighting}}
- Use specifications, not adjectives — `f/1.8`, `50mm`, `1/125s`, `ISO 400` beat "shallow depth of field".
- Authentic film characteristics: subtle grain, gentle color shift, soft highlight bloom, natural lens vignetting, true-to-stock color science. No digital over-sharpening, no clarity slider abuse.

Skin & realism
- Visible skin texture: micro pores, fine peach fuzz, a hint of unevenness in tone. A few subtle freckles or moles where natural.
- No plastic skin, no porcelain smoothing, no liquify, no airbrushing, no blemish removal.
- Hair has individual stray strands and natural volume — not a 3D wig.
- Fabric has real wrinkles and weight.

Composition
- Slightly off-center subject, generous negative space, intentional crop. Allow a part of the body or hair to bleed off-frame.
- The image should look like one frame from a roll of film — not a perfect studio capture.

Strict avoid
- No watermark, no text overlay, no caption.
- No glossy retouched skin, no symmetrical Instagram-filter look, no over-saturated color.
- No extra limbs, no warped hands, no melted earrings, no broken anatomy.
- No fake bokeh balls, no plastic catchlight stars, no AI-style "painted" eyes.

Output aspect ratio: {{aspect_ratio}}.

