Generate ONE 360° equirectangular panoramic image (full 360°×180° projection) of:

{{place}}

This image must be a TRUE equirectangular projection — width:height ratio exactly 2:1, suitable for direct loading into VR viewers, Google Street View, real-estate platforms, or sphere viewers without further conversion.

Projection rules (critical — most equirectangular generations fail here)
- Aspect ratio strictly 2:1 (1536 × 768 here).
- Top edge of the image = the zenith (straight up). Bottom edge = the nadir (straight down).
- The horizon must run as a perfectly horizontal line across the vertical center of the image.
- Pixels near the top and bottom must be horizontally stretched (the standard equirectangular distortion). Do NOT render the top as a flat ceiling — it must wrap.
- Left and right edges must seamlessly tile (the right edge continues into the left edge). No visible seam.

Scene
- Type: {{place_type}}
- Time of day & ambient light: {{time_of_day}}
- Weather / atmosphere: {{weather}}
- Render style: {{render_style}}

Composition
- The viewer's primary focal point (centered horizontally, on the horizon line, facing the camera): {{focal_point}}
- The space behind the camera (which lands on the left and right edges of the equirectangular image) must be equally finished — do not leave it blank or repetitive.
- Distribute light sources around the full 360° so the resulting sphere feels balanced (no half-lit panorama).

Quality
- Crisp detail across the full sphere, including the floor / ground (which gets compressed into the bottom strip) and the ceiling / sky (top strip).
- No camera tripod or photographer visible at the nadir (the bottom). If a tripod artifact would be there, paint it out cleanly with the surrounding floor.
- Materials read true-to-life: wood grain, fabric weave, metal reflectivity, glass transparency.

Strict avoid
- Do NOT output a flat rectangular landscape image labeled as panoramic. It must be a real equirectangular projection with the polar stretching at top and bottom.
- No visible vertical seam at the wrap-around edges.
- No people unless explicitly described in {{place}}.
- No watermark, no text overlay, no compass icon, no UI chrome.
- No fisheye distortion (fisheye is a different projection — we want equirectangular).

——————
